task.summary: Default task
Attempting to change operators in general-case single or multi-replicate operators.

TASSEL_GWAS.ipynb implements multi-replicate runs of the simulator. Stores all related parameter files in .yaml format using a new function. Creates a configFile to run TASSEL for each replicate using a .xml template.
Minor changes to simulator output. Parmeter sets for every replicate are written to files with corresponding names. Added a batch script gwas_pipeline.cmd to run multiple replicates through TASSEL.
Consolidated many separate directories under a single pycharm project. Minor changes to some functions. Developing GWAS output analysis.
Consolidated many separate directories under a single pycharm project. Minor changes to some functions. Developing GWAS output analysis.
Prior commit had wgs-0.1.0 under a separate, private git repository.
Cleaning up separate git repositories.
Some changes to docs. Added some new functions to analyze.
General reorginzations, added typical parameter files in .yaml format. Renamed some modules to more descriptive names. Repaired code which calculates kinship matrix.
Updates and minor changes to parameters class Genotype
trying to fix error
Before converting storage functions to use h5py instead of pandas/PyTables.

Before changing "gather_allele_data" in analyze. Encountered problem when trying to use it in the magic1478 population. Attempting to use it solely on segregating loci to determine if the problem is due to fixed loci.
This is unbelievable. When I switched to a Linux OS for my laptop I never completed a full run with TASSEL. Everything is half finished and all the way broken. How did this happen to me?
TASSEL Association mapping up and running. First set of output is under the run id "vandaleer". Does not make use of the function "multiple_sample_analyzer" but performs each step manually.

Created the Rscript file which runs the Q value calculation and outputs the results formatted for further processing in Python. The notebook I developed the Rscript in is "creating_the_q_value_R_script.ipynb" and the actual Rscript is "q_value_calculation.r". The script is called with the run id parameter.

Creating new functions to aid in interepretation of TASSEL results. Adding function to parameters.Trait which relates the minor and major alleles to their effect. Existing functions do not directly relate the minor/major allele state and corresponding allele effect. Making slight changes to parameters.Trait class to be initialized to a population.
Decided not to change the parameters.Trait class after all. Eventually I will probably make "qtl" an init paramter. Added function Trait.construct_minor_major_effects to parameters.
Added the new function, debugged and tested it. It works! My first new working function in I have no idea how long.
Committing before moving all data collection and data storage functions in the 'analyze' module to analyze.Study.

Moved several functions to analyze.Study. Deprecated many functions in analyze because they were older versions of newer functions. The classes SingleGeneration and MetaGeneration are virtual clones of one another. I will probably end up merging the two into Study. Comitting before moving anything else around.

parameters module has different functions to do pretty much the same things. Same problem as the analyze module. I am deprecating the Trait.assign_allele_effects function and changing the inputs of Trait.construct_allele_effects_table.
Had to make small adjustment to Trait.construct_ae_array to allow for up to 6 allele states at a locus. small_scale_run.ipynb contains a run using the most recent/working version of all functions.

Deleted several functions from parameters and analyze. Having several versions of the same function with similar names is extremely confusing. Several of them were hard-coded or just completely useless.

Added the 'small_scale_run.ipynb' to VCS. It is useful as a model because it reflects all recent changes to saegus. I need to add methods in the GWAS module which create the TASSEL configuration files for each scenario: (single generation, multiple replicates), (multiple generations, single replicate) so on and so forth. I am currently testing the (single generation, multiple replicates) method.
